---
import VizPlaceholder from '../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section id="understanding" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      The problem
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      Understanding meta-harnesses
    </h2>

    <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      <p>
        AI models are getting better. But a better model doesn't help an agent
        overcome certain boundaries. Agents only reach a small part of the
        organization's codebase. They don't remember what happened in the past.
        They don't coordinate PRs and CI. Those are
        <mark>structural limits, not intelligence limits</mark>.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400">
        Picture a single change to a shared UI library. To land it, someone
        explains the change to the first module that consumes the library, then
        to the second module, then to the platform team downstream, then to
        whoever owns CI. The same change gets re-explained five, six, seven
        times, once at every boundary. An agent hits the same walls. It is
        boxed into one repository, and it forgets everything the moment the
        session ends.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400">
        Two axes describe every one of these walls. There is
        <mark>space</mark>: the agent is bound to the repo in front of it and
        can't see the code that depends on it. And there is
        <mark>time</mark>: the agent starts every session from scratch, with no
        memory of what was decided before.
      </p>
      <p class="font-medium text-neutral-100">Meta-harnesses remove them.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-5xl">
    <VizPlaceholder label="scroll storyline, a change rippling through four repos, an explanation counter ticking up, then splitting into two axes: space and time" />
  </div>
</section>
